																				<div class="sg-editor">
						
<p>Walk into any gym and youâ€™ll likely see someone training their biceps in the mirror. Without overthinking, itâ€™s also quite likely that theyâ€™ll be doing some kind of curl variation.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Curls are great because they use elbow flexion as the main movement pattern. However, the degree of bicep isolation depends on the technique.</p>



<p>The specific movement patterns used in bicep isolation exercises reduce the risk of shoulder involvement. When done correctly, this provides a bigger exercise stimulus. If you want well-developed biceps, bicep isolation exercises are well worth the time commitment.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Below, we provide instructions on the best bicep isolation exercises, along with their benefits.</p>



<div class="wp-block-group ft-snippet is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<p class="has-medium-font-size">6 Best Bicep Isolation Exercises</p>



<p>These are the best bicep isolation exercises to focus on in 2025:</p>



<ul>
<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Concentration-Curl">Dumbbell Concentration Curl.</a></li>



<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Hammer-Curl">Dumbbell Hammer Curl.&nbsp;</a></li>



<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Preacher-Curl">Dumbbell Preacher Curl.</a></li>



<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Zottman-Preacher-Curl">Dumbbell Zottman Preacher Curl.</a></li>



<li><a href="#Cable-Preacher-Curl">Cable Preacher Curl.</a></li>



<li><a href="#Dumbbell-Bicep-Curl">Dumbbell Bicep Curl.&nbsp;</a></li>
</ul>



<p>Each of these exercises provides a slightly different bicep training stimulus. Theyâ€™re presented in no particular order and can be adapted accordingly to your training style.</p>
</div></div>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start"><strong><strong>6 Top Bicep Isolation Exercises</strong></strong></h2>



<p>Each of the exercises below is one of the best ones for isolating your biceps. Weâ€™ve presented them in no particular order.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Concentration-Curl"><strong>Dumbbell Concentration Curl</strong></h3>



<p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-concentration-curl" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dumbbell concentration curls</a> use the same elbow flexion movement as standard dumbbell curls. However, they use a slight forward lean with your leg as a bench support.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The primary mover is your biceps short head. Secondary movers include your biceps long head, brachialis, brachioradialis, and wrist flexors. These are the key elbow flexors of the upper body.</p>



<p>When your thigh acts as an arm support, it reduces the risk of shoulder involvement. Alongside this, it works one arm at a time, helping to work on potential muscular imbalances.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Dumbbell Concentration Curls" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/990003755?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption"><br>Dumbbell Concentration Curl Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Do</strong></h4>



<ol>
<li>Sit on the edge of a flat bench with your feet wider than shoulder-width apart. Your toes should be pointing slightly outwards.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Hold a dumbbell in one hand and rest it on the same thigh. Use a neutral grip with your palm facing inwards.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core. Lean forward slightly and rest your other arm on your other knee. Ensure you maintain a neutral back position throughout.</li>



<li>While looking down at your working arm, exhale and curl the dumbbell towards your shoulder.</li>



<li>Pause briefly at the top position. Inhale and bring the dumbbell back to the starting position under control.</li>



<li>After the stated reps, switch arms and repeat.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul>
<li>Rest your non-working hand on your knee to provide balance as you curl.&nbsp;</li>



<li>Keep your head in a neutral position facing the curl motion to minimize neck strain.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps</h4>



<div class="wp-block-group medicine-table is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<figure class="wp-block-table table-custom h-title table-border" style="font-size:16px;font-style:normal;font-weight:500"><table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Training Style</p></th><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Sets</p></th><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Reps</p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Strength Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3â€“5</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">4â€“6</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Hypertrophy</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3-4</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">8â€“10</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Endurance Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3-4</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">12â€“20</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Power Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3â€“5</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">1â€“3 (Explosive)</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps of Dumbbell Concentration Curl</figcaption></figure>
</div></div>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Hammer-Curl"><strong>Dumbbell Hammer Curl</strong></h3>



<p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-hammer-curl" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dumbbell hammer curls</a> use the same traditional dumbbell bicep curl movement. However, you curl the dumbbell using a neutral grip with your palms facing inward. This shifts the focus onto other elbow flexors, giving you an alternative isolation exercise that ensures well-rounded development.</p>



<p>The primary movers are your biceps long head, brachialis, and brachioradialis. Secondary movers include your biceps short head and wrist extensors. These stabilize your arm and support the primary elbow flexion movement.</p>



<p>Adding dumbbell hammer curls to your routine improves muscle definition, grip strength, and forearm mobility.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Dumbbell Hammer Curl" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/963023172?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Hammer Curl Guide. <span>Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</span></figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Do</strong></h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand straight with your feet shoulder-width apart. Your chest should be up with your hips facing forward.</li>



<li>Hold a dumbbell at each side using a neutral grip, palms facing inwards.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core. Exhale and bring the dumbbells up to shoulder height. Keep your elbows tucked in while only moving your forearms.</li>



<li>Pause at the top position and squeeze both biceps.</li>



<li>Inhale and lower the dumbbells back to the starting position under control.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul>
<li>Keep a neutral grip as you curl the dumbbell, palms facing inward.</li>



<li>Ensure you perform the curl using a full arc motion rather than bringing your shoulders slightly back.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



<div class="wp-block-group medicine-table is-layout-constrained wp-block-group-is-layout-constrained"><div class="wp-block-group__inner-container">
<figure class="wp-block-table table-custom h-title table-border" style="font-size:16px;font-style:normal;font-weight:500"><table class="has-fixed-layout"><thead><tr><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Training Style</p></th><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Sets</p></th><th class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center"><p class="pri-color-1">Reps</p></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Strength Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3â€“5</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">4â€“6</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Hypertrophy</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3-4</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">8â€“10</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Endurance Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3-4</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">12â€“20</td></tr><tr><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">Power Training</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">3â€“5</td><td class="has-text-align-center" data-align="center">1â€“3 (Explosive)</td></tr></tbody></table><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Optimal Sets &amp; Reps of Dumbbell Hammer Curl</figcaption></figure>
</div></div>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Preacher-Curl"><strong>Dumbbell Preacher Curl</strong></h3>



<p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-preacher-curl" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Dumbbell preacher curls</a> take the foundational elbow flexion movement and add a preacher bench underneath your upper arms. This eliminates potential shoulder movement, giving you an excellent bicep isolation exercise.</p>



<p>The primary mover is your biceps short head. Secondary movers include your biceps long head, brachialis, and wrist flexors.&nbsp;</p>



<p>The preacher bench makes it a great bicep isolation exercise. It also helps build strength, increase muscle definition, and promote overall arm stability.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="Dumbbell Preacher Curl" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/989035524?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Preacher Curl Guide. <span>Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</span></figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Do</strong></h4>



<ol>
<li>Start by adjusting the seat of the preacher bench so your chest is level with the pad.</li>



<li>Grab a suitable pair of dumbbells from the rack and hold them by your sides, palms facing in.</li>



<li>Sit on the seat and bring your arms onto the preacher bench. Ensure your chest is against the bench with your arms extended in front of you. Use a supinated grip with your palms facing upwards.</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core. Exhale and curl the dumbbells towards your shoulders.</li>



<li>Squeeze both biceps at the top position. Inhale and bring the dumbbells back to the starting position under control.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips&nbsp;</strong></h4>



<ul>
<li>Ensure your feet remain flat on the floor while using the preacher bench.</li>



<li>Keep your chest against the preacher pad to avoid potential lower back strain.</li>
</ul>



